{
  "texts": [
    "Although the A-D Principle as stated above has sometimes been presented as Anscombe and Davidson's major joint contribution to action theory, an emerging scholarly consensus has it that the two philosophers meant quite different things by their superficially similar formulas (see essays collected in Ford et al., 2011; Wiseman, 2017; see also Annas, 1976; Anscombe, 1979).",
    "Of the two, Davidson's is much closer to what has become the standard version of the principle -itself an integral part of action theory's standard story.",
    "But, as we'll see, this received metaphysics of human agency is incompatible with HEC.",
    "Far from supporting it, the A-D Principle provides theoretical grounds to resist the argument sketched above.",
    "First, let's get the view itself on the table."
  ]
}